questiontext.text:
A blockchain company {1:SHORTANSWER:%100%bought} a $95,000 Banksy artwork, burned it and broadcast it live on Twitter.
The company behind the stunt {1:SHORTANSWER:%100%is called} Injective Protocol
The event {1:SHORTANSWER:%100%took} place in an undisclosed Brooklyn neighborhood.
It {1:SHORTANSWER:%100%was streamed} through the Twitter account BurntBanksy.
Moments later, Injective Protocol employees {1:SHORTANSWER:%100%created} a digital representation of the art using blockchain technology.
Although digital art recently {1:SHORTANSWER:%100%has become} popular, this event was unique
It is the first major instance in which a physical artwork {1:SHORTANSWER:%100%was turned} into a unique digital asset.
We {1:SHORTANSWER:%100%view} this burning event as an expression of art itself, the CEO of Injective Protocol said.
He added, We specifically {1:SHORTANSWER:%100%chose} a Banksy piece since he has previously shredded one of his own artworks at an auction.

generalfeedback.text:
A blockchain company bought a $95,000 Banksy artwork, burned it and broadcast it live on Twitter.
The company behind the stunt is called Injective Protocol
The event took place in an undisclosed Brooklyn neighborhood.
It was streamed through the Twitter account BurntBanksy.
Moments later, Injective Protocol employees created a digital representation of the art using blockchain technology.
Although digital art recently has become popular, this event was unique
It is the first major instance in which a physical artwork was turned into a unique digital asset.
We view this burning event as an expression of art itself, the CEO of Injective Protocol said.
He added, We specifically chose a Banksy piece since he has previously shredded one of his own artworks at an auction.
